==Intel chips flaw investigation==
{{Further|Intel_Atom#Issues}}

On 6 February 2017, ''The Register'' was the first news outlet to accurately trace a recently discovered flaw in Cisco (and other makers) gear to a serious defect on [[Intel]]'s Atom C2000 series processors.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | author=Thomas Claburn | publisher=The Register | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2017/02/06/cisco_intel_decline_to_link_product_warning_to_faulty_chip/ | title=FYI: Intel's Atom C2000 chips are bricking products – and it's not just Cisco hit | date=February 6, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Further|Meltdown (security vulnerability)|Spectre (security vulnerability)}}
Around 3 January 2018, ''The Register'' broke news about Google's long-ongoing investigation into Intel's processor design, which revealed that a serious flaw in the design of their chips would require Microsoft, Linux and Apple to update operating systems for computers around the world.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-42553818|title=Major flaw in millions of Intel chips|last=Wakefield|first=Jane|date=2018|work=BBC News|access-date=20 January 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706013820/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-42553818|archive-date=6 July 2018|url-status=live}}&lt;/ref&gt;

